      "type": "Person",
      "front": "Henry David Thoreau",
      "back": "Transcendentalist critic of conformity. Emerson's Concord, Massachusetts, neighbor, the writer Henry David Thoreau, echoed his call for individual self-reliance. \"Any man more right than his neighbors,\" Thoreau wrote, \"is a majority of one.\" Ironies abounded in the era's \"individualism\" (a term that first entered the language in the 1820s). Henry David Thoreau appears throughout The Market Revolution as a major historical actor.",
