      "chapterId": "chapter9",
      "type": "Event",
      "front": "Eli Whitney's cotton gin",
      "back": "In the first half of the nineteenth century, in rapid succession, the steamboat, canal, railroad, and telegraph wrenched America out of its economic past. These innovations opened new land to settlement, lowered transportation costs, and made it far easier for economic enterprises to sell their products. They linked farmers to national and world markets and made them major consumers of manufactured goods.",
